# FakeTwitter HQ üïäÔ∏è

A responsive Twitter/X timeline clone. Vanilla HTML/CSS/JS ‚Äî no build step, no
dependencies, so it deploys to Netlify by drag-and-drop.

## Files
- `index.html` ‚Äî Home timeline (sidebar, tweet composer, feed, trends, who to follow)
- `explore.html` ‚Äî Explore page with category filters and search
- `login.html` ‚Äî Demo login page (any email + 4+ char password logs you in)
- `styles.css` ‚Äî All styling, including the responsive breakpoints and dark theme
- `script.js` ‚Äî Tweet data, rendering, like/retweet/reply logic, dark mode, modal

## How the marks map to what's here

**Base Twitter Timeline Clone (40)** ‚Äî `index.html` + `styles.css`: three-column
layout (nav sidebar / feed / trends sidebar), tweet composer, tweet feed with
avatars, verified badges, hashtags, action icons and counts. Responsive from a
4K ultrawide down to a small Android screen (icon-only sidebar at ~1265px,
sidebar collapses to a bottom nav + floating action button under 688px).

**Custom feature ‚Äî NO Cursor (15)** ‚Äî **dark mode toggle**. The toggle, the
`data-theme="dark"` CSS variable swap in `styles.css`, and the `initTheme()`
function in `script.js` are simple enough to type by hand in one sitting.
üëâ Before you submit: re-type this feature yourself in your own editor,
without AI assistance, so you can genuinely explain every line in your Loom
video. Use what's here as a reference/spec, not as a paste job ‚Äî that's the
whole point of the mark allocation. A good way to do it: delete the
`theme-toggle` CSS block and `initTheme()` function, then rebuild them from
scratch using the class names already wired up in the HTML (`.theme-checkbox`,
`data-theme`).

**Custom features ‚Äî WITH Cursor (10+10)**
1. **Tweet compose modal** (`#modalOverlay` in the HTML, `openModal`/`closeModal`
   in `script.js`) ‚Äî clicking "Tweet" or the reply icon opens a centered modal
   composer, matching the real X "what's happening" popup.
2. **Explore page** (`explore.html`) ‚Äî category tabs (Trending/News/Sports/
   Entertainment), live search-as-you-type filtering, and a "who to follow"
   grid.

**Bonus already included beyond the brief:** a working login page with
floating labels and validation, likes/retweets/posts persist across reloads
via `localStorage`, and a toast notification system for feedback.

## Running locally
No build tools needed. Either:
```
open index.html
```
or serve it (recommended, avoids any file:// quirks):
```
python3 -m http.server 8000
```
then visit `http://localhost:8000`.

## Deploying to Netlify
1. Go to [app.netlify.com/drop](https://app.netlify.com/drop)
2. Drag this whole folder onto the page
3. Netlify gives you a live `.netlify.app` URL instantly ‚Äî that's your
   submission link
(Or connect it as a GitHub repo in Netlify for auto-deploys on every push.)

